[2]
Date: 27 Feb 2008
Source: The Advocate, Baton Rouge [edited]
<http://www.2theadvocate.com>


The Ascension Parish school system will have to dispose of more than
14 000 pounds of beef due to a recent voluntary recall by a
California meat company of 143 million pounds of its raw and frozen
beef, a school system spokesman said Tuesday [26 Feb 2008].

Hallmark/Westland Meat Packing Co. recalled the beef because it was
determined to be unfit for humans after the cattle did not receive
complete and proper inspection, according to a USDA news release.

Johnnie Balfantz, public information officer for the Ascension
schools, said school district authorities found out last week that
beef supplies stored in a warehouse freezer and in some school
freezers are part of a 2nd wave of nationwide beef recalls. Balfantz
said the school system has to dispose of 835 cases of beef. Each case
contains about 17 pounds. The school system's warehouse freezer off
Airline Highway in Sorrento has about 661 cases on hand, while the
remaining 174 cases are scattered among several school freezers,
Balfantz said. He said that all 835 cases will be trucked soon to a
local dump site, following USDA regulations. Balfantz said school
officials don't yet have a date or a location for getting rid of the
beef.

