******
[3]
Date: 27 Feb 2008
Source: Wall Street Journal [edited]
<http://online.wsj.com/article/SB120407469460895261.html?mod=googlenews_wsj>


The nation's largest meat recall expanded to include processed foods
that used the meat, as 2 of the world's largest packaged-food
companies said yesterday [26 Feb 2008] that they are recalling
products. Also yesterday, the president of the California company at
the center of the recall failed to appear before a congressional
food-safety hearing, and leading Democrats are now considering
whether to subpoena him to testify. Steve Mendell, head of
Hallmark/Westland Meat Packing Co. in Chino, California, didn't show
up to answer questions before a panel of the Energy and Commerce
Committee. The company, a top supplier for the national school-lunch
program, recently recalled 143 million pounds of beef after a Humane
Society video showed cruel treatment of animals and violations of
federal regulations.

General Mills Inc., Minneapolis said it has recalled 35 000 cases of
its Progresso Italian Wedding soup because it contained beef from a
supplier that got meat from the Hallmark/Westland plant. General
Mills initiated the recall Friday [22 Feb 2008], a company
spokeswoman said. She couldn't say whether all of the product had
been removed from grocery store shelves yet. Each case of soup
contains between 6 and 12 cans.

Nestle Prepared Foods Co., which is part of Nestle SA of Switzerland,
said it has recalled some boxes of its Hot Pockets sandwiches that
contain beef from a vendor that used Hallmark/Westland. The varieties
include some Hot Pockets Philly Steak & Cheese sandwiches as well as
some Hot Pockets Croissant Crust Philly Steak & Cheese sandwiches
that were sold in 2-pack boxes.

A Nestle Prepared Foods spokeswoman said the recall encompasses about
49 000 cases of Hot Pockets, with each case containing 8 boxes of the
sandwiches. She said the company told retailers to remove the product
from stores on Friday [22 Feb 2008] but that retailers probably are
still working to get all of the product out of their system.
Supermarket chain Supervalu Inc., based in Eden Prairie, Minnesota,
said it has started to remove the Progresso soup and Hot Pockets
items as well as some frozen ground-beef patties linked to the recall
from its stores.

A spokeswoman for Hormel Foods Corp., Austin, Minnesota said no
Hormel products had been recalled. But one of the company's
subsidiaries, Farmer John's, based in Southern California, will be
recalling a "small amount" of hot dogs and cotto salami, she said.

Meanwhile, Committee Chairman John Dingell and investigations panel
Chairman Bart Stupak, both Michigan Democrats, weren't happy when Mr.
Mendell didn't appear at the congressional hearing. "It appears he
has refused our offer to testify voluntarily," Mr. Dingell said of
Mr. Mendell. "We now will have to consider whether we need to compel
his appearance to probe how onsite USDA inspectors could have missed
these safety problems and the inhumane treatment of the animals that
were slaughtered there."

[Byline: Jane Zhang, Janet Adamy, David Kesmodel]

